@oaklandmatt I feel like what you’re saying is super applicable to the pop game, but from what I can tell @cian riordan is transforming mixes and Jon is amplifying peoples visions. I think Cian has mentioned this in regards to Jon mixing songs in a few hours because a lot of decisions are made vs what Cian does which is taking more raw tracks. (Let’s say indie vs pop music if that makes sense

I don’t mean to say what Jon does is “less than” by any means. His mixes are fucking insane and I’m addicted to his work.

Thanks for coming to my Ted talk, presented by white wine.

@oaklandmatt Thank you for the suggestions.

I'm very close to this point now. I'm doing 4 octave scale runs with both hands at various tempos to focus on consistency of fingering and of tone. The next frontier is doing a variation of these runs where one hand starts on a scale different interval (going up in 3rds, 4ths, etc...)

The exercise that's challenging me at the moment has been doing wide arpeggios (sometimes with intervals of a 7th or more) up and down a two octaves. I'm taking it slow and becoming more consistent, but I know I'm likely to start hitting a wall as I get them up to a quicker tempo, hence the renewed focus on really getting my technique right at these tempos.

I've very much internalized the concept of "Slow is smooth. Smooth is fast." I'm starting things slow and not moving on until I can do them flawlessly at glacial tempos.

@ehutton21 I think you're right about a teacher. LA is undoubtedly full of good ones. A lesson a week should help me to orient myself in the right direction.

Thank you for all of the insight.

@oaklandmatt @spectrummasters I want y'all to gas me up more on these points. These ideas are beautiful. I feel this at a human level. I don't share your lack of concern, but want more evidence to fuel some hope. It seems to me much about the way information (music included) travels online from a systems view is misaligned with these values / ideals and generative AI / fake artists will just make it worse. I don't mean to highjack the convo either so can move this to a thread if that makes sense.
"I think a part of being a human is that we intrinsically move towards the authentic and not the imitation"
"This part of it I'm not actually worried about. Human beings continue to want to connect to other human beings, and music is still fundamentally a way to connect one person to another."
